AB  - The author notes that (1) there exists mixed empirical evidence on the choice of technology by foreign firms vis-a-vis local firms in developing countries, and (2) there is a recent argument that Japanese multinationals behave differently from American multinational. This paper goes on to examine the choice of technology by foreign and local firms in four major industries in Hong kong. It is found that foreign and local firms tend to use very similar factor proportions and that there are no significant differences between Japanese firms, and American and European firms. Finally, this paper argues that an electric approach should be used to explain the choice of technology by foreign and local firms in developing countries. In this approach, the product life cycle and the stage of economic development in the host country should both be considered.
