AB  - This paper presents an overview of the development of conditionality and financial programming techniques used by the IMF. The current analytical framework underlying IMF conditionality is described and critically appraised. Questions are raised on the consistency of the approach followed on the issue of devaluation with the overall framework, on the length of programs and the costs of adjustment in cases of structural disequilibria. The conclusion is reached that, whilst existing financial programming techniques are valid for certain cases, they would need to be revised and supplemented to make them relevant to other cases. Some suggestions for improvement of the Fund's operational procedures are made.
