UR  - https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/030438788390038X
AB  - The estimates for the money demand equation reported below are based on quarterly time series for Brazil for the 1966-I–1979-IV period. They show that the long-run income elasticity of the demand for money is roughly unitary and the rate of interest does affect the demand for money. Exclusion of the latter variable therefore leads to biased estimates of the coefficients of the money demand equation. The empirical evidence also points out that the rate of inflation affects the demand for money only to the extent that it is necessary to change nominal cash balances to adjust cash holdings to their desired level. Either nominal interest rates capture the expected inflation rates, or goods inventories are not an important alternative to holding money in Brazil.
ER  - 

