UR  - https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/0304387883900330
AB  - This article argues that although social security has had a significant impact in preventing a considerable number of people from falling below the extreme poverty level in Latin America, it has not played an important role in reducing current extreme poverty in the region. The analysis is done focusing on three social security objectives: protection of the needy affected by social risks; progressive income redistribution; and promotion of savings-investment to reduce inflation and enhance development. The author discusses a series of recommendations for achievement of the three cited objectives in order to diminish critical poverty in the future.
